<div class="prose">

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">How to use this page</div>
  Copy the template below into your submission — last page of the doc, last slide of the deck, or a final paragraph in a written piece. Fill all six fields. Submit alongside your work in Google Classroom.
</div>

<h2>The template</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Field</th><th>What goes here</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Tool(s) used</strong></td>
      <td>Name and version of every AI tool you used. <em>Example:</em> "Gemini 2.5 Flash (May 2026)"; "Claude Sonnet 4.6"; "Plate Tectonics Tutor (BoodleBox box)". List all if you used more than one.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Prompts (representative)</strong></td>
      <td>1–3 of the prompts that shaped the work most. Quote them. <em>You don't need every prompt</em> — just the ones that mattered.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What the AI contributed</strong></td>
      <td>Specific tasks: brainstorming, outlining, drafting a paragraph, giving feedback, translating, summarizing a source, explaining a concept. Be specific — "it helped me" is not enough.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What YOU contributed</strong></td>
      <td>Your decisions, your evidence selection, your interpretation, your voice, your final edits, your conclusions. This should be the bulk of the work.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>OPVL of the AI's contribution</strong></td>
      <td>A short OPVL on the AI as a source for this specific work. Highlight especially the <strong>Limitations</strong> — what was it wrong about, what did you fix, what couldn't it do? See <a href="/foundations/opvl-framework/">OPVL Framework</a> for a refresher.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>One thing the AI got wrong</strong></td>
      <td><strong>Required.</strong> Name at least one specific thing the AI got wrong, missed, refused, or couldn't do well. If you couldn't find one, that's a sign you weren't checking carefully enough.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">Two non-negotiable rules</div>
  <p><strong>K/U gate.</strong> If this template is missing or trivially completed, your K/U score on that assessment cannot exceed 3–4 regardless of how strong the rest of the work is.</p>
  <p><strong>T/T gate.</strong> If you can't identify a specific thing the AI got wrong, your T/T cannot exceed 5–6. The "one thing it got wrong" field is the metacognitive move T/T is built to detect.</p>
</div>

<h2>Need to understand why each field exists?</h2>

<p>The <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Protocol</a> in Foundations explains the reasoning behind each field, lists the AI failure modes to watch for, and walks through three worked examples (strong, weak, and the violation). Read it once at the start of the year; come back when you're unsure what counts as "specific enough."</p>

<h2>Mini-version — for incidental AI use only</h2>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">When the full template is overkill</div>
  <p>For very minor AI use (one prompt, low-stakes task — e.g. "Gemini translated one paragraph from Hindi"), use the three-field mini-version:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tool + one prompt</strong></li>
    <li><strong>What I did with it</strong></li>
    <li><strong>One thing it got wrong (or that I had to fix)</strong></li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Default to the full template for graded work.</strong> The mini is for incidental use that doesn't shape the deliverable. If in doubt, use the full template.</p>
</div>

<h2>If you're unsure whether your use needs documentation</h2>

<blockquote>"Could I explain to my teacher exactly what I did, and would I be comfortable doing so?"</blockquote>

<p>If yes, document it and submit. If no, stop and recalibrate. See <a href="/foundations/class-expectations/">Class Expectations</a> for the full disclosure principle.</p>

</div>
